<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n26263f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26263f">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26263f"> 263(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> hand marriage</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The Law of the Family Relations]</font>&mdash;As regards divorce, Cicero alludes vaguely to a provision in the Tables about a man depriving his wife of the house-keys and turning her out of doors, with some such words as &ldquo;take what is thine and get thee gone.&rdquo; This can only refer to free or non-<i>manus</i> marriages, but even for <mark>hand marriages</mark>, while repudiations by husbands (but not by wives) were competent, the statement of the historians is that they were few and far between &hellip; <small> &ldquo;ROMAN LAW&rdquo; <a name="EBRL2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBRL2"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 540</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
